******
[2] France: Institut de Veille Sanitaire - monthly statistics as of
Tue 1 Mar 2011 - no new vCJD cases
Date: Tue 1 Mar 2011
Source: IVS - Maladie de Creutzfeldt-Jakob et maladies apparentees
[in French, trans. & summ. Mod.CP, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/display/?doc=publications/mcj/donnees_mcj.html>


During the 1st 2 months of 2011, there were 290 referrals, 3
confirmed fatal cases of sporadic CJD, and none of familial CJD,
iatrogenic CJD, or vCJD.

A total of 25 cases of confirmed or probable vCJD have been recorded
in France since records began in 1992. There was 1 case in 1996, 1 in
2000, 1 in 2001, 3 in 2002, 2 in 2004, 6 in 2005, 6 in 2006, 3 in
2007, 2 in 2009, and none in 2010 and 2011.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[3] USA: National Prion Disease Pathology Surveillance Center -
cumulative case numbers for 2010 up to 1 Nov 2010 - no vCJD cases
Date: Mon 1 Nov 2010
Source: US National Prion Disease Pathology Surveillance Center
[edited]
<http://www.cjdsurveillance.com/pdf/case-table.pdf>


Cumulative data 1 Jan 2010 to 31 October 2010
---------------------------------------------
During the 10 month period 1 Jan 2010 to 31 Oct 2010, there were 333
referrals, 213 of whom were classified as prion disease cases,
comprising 158 cases of sporadic CJD, 33 of familial CJD, and none of
iatrogenic CJD or vCJD.

Overall of 3831 referrals examined since screening began in 1996 or
thereabouts, diagnosis is still pending in 18 cases, and another 18
cases have been considered inconclusive. [This is a measure of the
difficulty in achieving unequivocal diagnoses. - Mod.CP]

During the same period a total of 2265 prion disease cases have been
screened, a figure which includes 23 (22 during 2010) cases with type
determination pending, but in which a diagnosis of vCJD has been
excluded. 3 cases of vCJD recorded in the USA during the same period
have been attributed to infection in the UK in 2 cases, and in Saudi
Arabia in the other.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[4] UK: HPA biannual update
Date: Fri 11 Feb 2011
Source: Health Protection Agency (HPA) report, 5(6) [summ, edited]
<http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/infections/ei_cjd.htm#cjd1101>


Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) biannual update (2011/1)
--------------------------------------------------------
This 6 monthly report provides an update on reports of incidents of
potential iatrogenic (healthcare acquired) exposure to CJD, and on the
National Anonymous Tonsil Archive. The data are correct as of 26 Jan
2011.

For numbers of CJD case reports, readers should consult data provided
by the national CJD Surveillance Unit (NCJDSU), Edinburgh
(<http://www.cjd.ed.ac.uk/figures.htm>, or part [1] of this Prion
Update). The latest yearly analysis of vCJD reports (onsets and
deaths) is also available from the NCJDSU website
[<http://www.cjd.ed.ac.uk/vcjdqdec06.htm>].

Reports of incidents of potential iatrogenic exposure to CJD via
surgery: 2000 to 31 Dec 2010

A surgical incident occurs when a patient with or at risk of CJD has
undergone surgery without the appropriate infection control guidance
being followed [<http://www.dh.gov.uk/ab/ACDP/TSEguidance/index.htm>].
This could happen if a patient undergoes surgery during the incubation
period of CJD, or because information about CJD risk factors is not
available at the time of surgery. If this happens, surgical
instruments that may be contaminated with the infectious agent that
causes CJD, could pose a transmission risk when they are reused on
other patients.

Advice has been issued for the 20 surgical incidents that were
reported to the CJD Incidents Panel in 2010. The number of CJD
surgical incidents reported to the CJD Incidents Panel from 2000 to 31
Dec 2010 by the diagnosis of the index patient are shown in a table in
the original text. Overall, 45 per cent of surgical incidents result
from surgery on index cases diagnosed with sporadic CJD.

Information about the CJD Incidents Panel can be found on the HPA
website
[<http://www.hpa.org.uk/web/HPAweb&Page&HPAwebAutoListName/Page/1204031511121>].

The HPA report also contains detailed information on:
- surgical incidents resulting in at-risk patients: since 2000 to 31
Dec 2010, there have been 25 surgical incidents, in which the Panel
has advised that 158 patients should be considered to have an
increased risk of CJD.
- patient denotifications
- current "at-risk" patients resulting from surgical instruments:
there are 12 surgical incidents in which 120 patients are still
considered to be at risk of CJD.

Currently, 78 of these at-risk patients have been notified that they
are at risk of CJD. Local decisions have been taken not to notify 4
patients in these incidents. The Panel is currently advising on one
other incident in which approximately 18 at-risk patients (one of whom
is known to have died) are to be advised that they have an increased
risk of CJD.
- reports of blood incidents 1 Jan 2010 to 31 Dec 2010: the diagnosis
in 2009 of a vCJD case, who had previously received blood
transfusions, resulted in 10 individuals being identified as alive and
at risk of vCJD. 2 of these individuals had donated blood to the case,
and 8 others had received blood components from these 2 donors. 9 of
these patients were notified of their exposure and asked to follow
public health advice. A local decision was taken not to notify the
10th recipient.
- monitoring of patients "at increased risk" of CJD: the CJD
Incidents Panel and the ACDP [Advisory Committee on Dangerous
Pathogens] TSE Working Group have identified a range of individuals
and groups who may have been exposed to an increased risk of CJD as a
consequence of their medical care. The risks of iatrogenic CJD
transmission to these different individuals are very uncertain, but
potentially devastating. The CJD Incidents Panel has advised that
these individuals are informed of their risk and asked to follow
public health precautions to avoid transmitting the infection to
others.
- 6 monthly update on the National Anonymous Tonsil Archive -- end of
January 2011: the National Anonymous Tonsil Archive (NATA) has
received a total of 91 083 tonsil pairs up to the end of January 2011
from hospitals in England and Scotland, about 17 419 of which are from
the birth cohort of in which most vCJD cases have arisen (1961-1985).
A further 3000 tonsil pairs have been received from the Medical
Research Council Prion Unit at UCL Institute for Neurology, National
Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery. Therefore the total number of
tonsil pairs in the archive as at end of January was 94 083. The
number of collection forms that were completed but no tonsil tissue
collected was 2 509 (1 643 due to patient objection and 871 due to
clinical pathology being requested).

--
communicated by:
Terry S Singeltary Sr
