[6] Taiwan: suspected case statement
Date: Tue 15 Feb 2011
Source: Focus Taiwan, Central News Agency (CNA) report [edited]
<http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?ID=201102150035&Type=aLIV>


Department of Health censured for downplaying probable human mad cow
disease death
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Department of Health (DOH) was censured by the Control Yuan [see
comment below] on Tuesday [15 Feb 2011] for downplaying a probable
case of death from [variant] Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) last year
[2010]. The top government watchdog said the incident indicates that
the DOH lacks a flexible mechanism to guide the release of information
on major diseases. The way the DOH handled the incident was
questionable because it failed to clear up the truth or disperse
people's doubts about the case, the Control Yuan said.

A Taiwanese man, who lived in the United Kingdom [UK] from 1989 to
1997, died in May 2010 from what appeared to be [variant] CJD, a
disease linked to eating tissue from cattle infected with bovine
spongiform encephalopathy [BSE], or mad cow disease. The patient, who
began to show symptoms such as memory loss and hypersomnia, was
reported to health authorities as a suspected CJD case in March 2009.
While the man's family refused to give permission for an autopsy, a
medical team determined that it was an "extremely likely case" of
[variant] CJD based on his MRI and EEG [magnetic resonance imaging and
electroencephalograms]. However, the DOH did not publish the details
until 8 Dec 2010, 6 months after his death and after the case had been
reported by local media.

According to the Control Yuan, the DOH chose to gloss over the
incident because at the time it was first reported to the health
authorities in March 2009, Taiwan was negotiating sensitive beef trade
issues with the United States. An investigation by the Control Yuan
shows that the DOH never notified the National Security Council --
which was leading the Taiwan-US beef trade talks -- about the
suspected CJD case.

This gave people the impression that the DOH's decision on whether to
release disease information was based solely on "political
considerations," the Control Yuan said.

[byline: Sophia Yeh, YF Low]

--
communicated by:
Terry S Singeltary Sr
<flounder9@verizon.net>

[The Control Yuan, one of the 5 branches of the Republic of China
government in Taipei, is an investigatory agency that monitors the
other branches of government. It may be compared to the Court of
Auditors of the European Union, the Government Accountability Office
of the United States, or a standing commission for administrative
inquiry (<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_Yuan>).

This suspected case of vCJD in Taiwan has been described in detail in
parts (4) and (5) of the ProMED-mail Prion disease update 2011 (01)
archive number 20110110.0119. Prion protein gene analysis showed that
the victim was homozygous for methionine at codon 129, but since the
victim's body was cremated it was not possible to confirm the
diagnosis by detection of a BSE-like prion. Diagnosis was based on
symptoms, magnetic resonance imaging, and electroencephalograms. The
fact that the patient had been resident for a lengthy period in the
UK, however, was compatible with the diagnosis of vCJD. It is likely
that the patient contracted vCJD while in the UK and even if it this
information had been disclosed, it would not have been an impediment
to the beef trade talks between officials in Taiwan and the USA.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Taiwan is available at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00tD>. - Mod.CP]
